"According to tradition, this is the cave referred to by Homer in The Odyssey. The nymph Calypso lived in this cave and it is where she entertained Ulysses for seven years before he resumed his journey. Calypso Cave is in fact a series of caves and, according to some, these extend right down to the sea." ❤

La Grotta di Calipso domina dall’alto la spiaggia rossa di Ramla l-Ħamra. Si ritiene che sia la grotta, dimora della ninfa Calipso, a cui Omero si riferiva nell’Odissea. Secondo la leggenda pare che l'odierna Gozo fosse l’omerica isola di Ogigia e che la grotta sia proprio quella dove la ninfa Calipso, innamoratasi perdutamente, tenne Ulisse come prigioniero per sette lunghi anni.

主人公オデュッセウスは船で難破しこのラムラ湾に辿り着き、やむなく洞窟で暮らしていたところ、そこへ絶世の美女カリプソが現れ、７年間もオデュッセウスを洞窟に引き止めていました。その後オデュッセウスは故郷へと旅立ってしまうのですが、残されたカリプソはその後もずっと洞窟からラムラ湾を眺め、オデュッセウスの帰りを待っていたという神話が残る。

High in the hills above Ramla Bay (Gozo) at the Calypso Cave area in Xaghra.
The cave was once open to the public but has recently closed due to "geological movement."
You can still access the walk way around the surrounding area and part of the viewpoint, allowing you to obtain these stunning views!

Calypso’s Cave overlooks the red sands of Gozo’s finest beach, Ramla Bay and is alleged to be the cave referred to by Homer in The Odyssey. The story goes that Gozo is Homer’s Island of Ogygia and the cave is the one where the beautiful nymph Calypso keeps Odysseus as a “prisoner of love” for seven years.

Depois de uma caminhadinha frustrada e uma carona abençoada (os malteses em Gozo são maravilhosos, receptivos e educados) cheguei numa placa: Calypso’s Cave... o caminho não parecia que me levaria pra tudoooo aquilo que falavam... realmente! Me levou pra um lugar ainda mais extraordinário! O paraíso! E eu?! Chorei, agradeci, contemplei! This is Ramla Bay on the north-east coast of Malta’s sister-isle Gozo, with its beautiful reddish-coloured sand (the word ‘ramla’ means a grain of sand in Maltese). And high up on the hillside where I am standing is Calypso’s Cave, a grotto supposedly inhabited by the nymph Calypso (although there is not much left to be seen of the cave today).
.
.
◻️In Greek mythology, nymphs were divine female spirits who animated nature and who were usually depicted as beautiful young maidens who loved to dance and sing.  In Homer’s book ‘The Odyssey’, written in the 9th Century BC, Odysseus (or Ulysses) was ‘amorously detained’ by the cunning Calypso after being shipwrecked off the coast of Sicily and drifting to the island of Ogygia (possibly Gozo). She managed to keep him prisoner in her cave for seven whole years, singing and weaving on her loom with a golden shuttle, hoping to make him her immortal husband.  However, Odysseus was already married to Penelope (who was known for her fidelity to her long-absent husband, despite having several would-be suitors) and he yearned to return to his wife.  His patron goddess Athena asked Zeus (the king of the gods) to order the release of Odysseus from the island and Calypso eventually conceded, sending him on his way after providing him with food and the materials to build a raft.
.
.
.

node.text: «Мужчина, развлечься не желаете?» я в роли нимфы по имени  Калипсо. ⠀В 15 минутах езды ( на Гозо вообще все - в 15 минутах езды))- находится та самая пещера- жилище нимфы Калипсо , которая когда- то заманила бедолагу Одиссея к себе на долгих 7 лет, когда он как примерный семьянин направлялся домой к Пенелопе из Трои. Вернее , пещера- то есть, но с 2012 года доступ в нее закрыт для туристов . Калипсо, видимо, не одобряла всех подряд визитеров, поэтому участились оползни и обвалы, что делало посещение пещеры мягко говоря небезопасным. Но осталась «наземная» часть жилища нимфы и смотровая площадка на скале,под которой находится пещера. #calypso#calypsoscave#gozo#malta#maltagram#travelgram#mytravelgram#travelphotography

Вид из «пещеры Калипсо» на красный пляж Рамла Бэй. Гозо очень отличается от остальной Мальты. Он более зеленый, более уютный, гораздо более спокойный и менее тусовочный, точней не тусовочный вообще.  Гиды утверждают, что около 20 процентов жителей Гозо никогда не покидали острова и даже не были на Мальте. А вот мальтийцы целыми семьями едут по выходным на пароме на Гозо- насладиться тишиной и особой атмосферой этого острова.

Entering the Calypso’s Cave area after an hour of hiking with our hopes up. Finding out that it’s closed from the public. Awkward 😅#traveller #gozoisland #calypsoscave #malta🇲🇹

To name fantastic geographical phenomena after places described only in myth is to completely ensnare human attention. Awe-ful places like this hardly require appellation, but to halo them in a story renders them irresistible. I love the myth-inspired name given to this cave. But it is inaccurate. 
In Homer's epic, Odysseus was shipwrecked on a mystical island and enchanted by the nymph goddess Calypso who dwelled in a cave. .
Lately I have been reading about feminine symbolism in myth, and caves are rife with it. The wombness of caves is unmistakable. They are primordially wet; dark yet moon-lured. Water is first. Life does not need light to begin, it huddles nascent, in Stygian waters and either dies or flourishes. .
The crone archetype, or feminine death entity, is embodied in caves as portals to the underworld. In epic tales, the hero is often tasked with a harrowing journey into a cave where the dead reside. The hero usually undergoes a symbolic death and/or comes by some kind of transformative influence. He emerges baptized by death, fulfilling the trope of rebirth, completing the ultimate cycle: life-death-life, which the feminine embodies. The womb where life begins and is transformed, whence life emerges and is returned. It is pan-thematic, inescapable. The magic of it leaves me breathless. The mystery of it chased my heart around my thoughts while I swam in indigo waves and pondered legends on the purple rocks of Calypso's cave. 
#mljet #calypsoscave #goddess #waternymph #mythlover #thesignshouldsaycalypsoscave

One of the best parts of visiting Malta (and Gozo) was seeing how unguarded and/or untouched many famous locations were. Of course, having my buddy @andresgl13 act as a local guide made it extra special and easy to visit the islands and see some of the favourite local spots. 
Calypso's Cave on the island of Gozo was by far one of the most magical places we saw. If you know me, you know I'm secretly 5 years old and love to get swept away by fantasy, sci fi and mythical stories. To sit where a Goddess supposedly lived and look out over this breathtaking bay was incredible. 
So there's no sustainability pitch here, aside from a plea to keep your sense of wonder, your little spark of madness and look for and appreciate the natural beauty that mother earth provides. Let that be enough reason to protect the earth.

The scent of citrus and of brittle pine suffused the island. Inside, she was singing and weaving with a shuttle made of gold. Her voice was beautiful. Around the cave a luscious forest flourished: alder, poplar, and scented cypress. It was full of wings. Birds nested there but hunted out at sea: the owls, the hawks, the gulls with gaping beaks. A ripe and luscious vine, hung thick with grapes, was stretched to coil around her cave. Four springs spurted with sparkling water as they laced with crisscross currents intertwined together. The meadow softly bloomed with celery and violets. He gazed around in wonder and joy, at sights to please even a god.

Odyssey, Book V.60-74
trans. Emily Wilson

Divine Calypso told her guest to sit upon a gleaming, glittering chair, and said, “Dear friend, Lord Hermes of the golden wand, why have you come? You do not often visit. What do you have in mind? My heart inclines to help you if I can, if it is fated. For now, come in, and let me make you welcome.” At that the goddess led him to a table heaped with ambrosia, and she mixed a drink: red nectar. So mercurial Hermes drank and ate till he was satisfied, and then the diplomat explained why he had come.

Odyssey, Book V.85-96
trans. Emily Wilson

Calypso "E il mare azzurro che l’amò, più oltre
spinse Odisseo, per nove giorni e notti,
e lo sospinse all’isola lontana,
alla spelonca, cui fioriva all’orlo
carica d’uve la pampinea vite.
E fosca intorno le crescea la selva
d’ontani e d’odoriferi cipressi;
e falchi e gufi e garrule cornacchie
v’aveano il nido. E non dei vivi alcuno,
nè dio nè uomo, vi poneva il piede.
Or tra le foglie della selva i falchi
battean le rumorose ale, e dai buchi
soffiavano, dei vecchi alberi, i gufi,
e dai rami le garrule cornacchie
garrian di cosa che avvenia nel mare.
Ed ella che tessea dentro cantando,
presso la vampa d’olezzante cedro,
stupì, frastuono udendo nella selva,
e in cuore disse: Ahimè, ch’udii la voce
delle cornacchie e il rifiatar dei gufi!
E tra le dense foglie aliano i falchi.
Non forse hanno veduto a fior dell’onda
un qualche dio, che come un grande smergo
viene sui gorghi sterili del mare?
O muove già senz’orma come il vento,
sui prati molli di viola e d’appio?
Ma mi sia lungi dall’orecchio il detto!
In odio hanno gli dei la solitaria
Nasconditrice. E ben lo so, da quando
l’uomo che amavo, rimandai sul mare
al suo dolore. O che vedete, o gufi
dagli occhi tondi, e garrule cornacchie?" (Giovanni Pascoli, "Poemi conviviali", "L'ultimo viaggio", XXIVl)

#DeRoce Ramla Bay is located at the bottom of a rich and fertile valley on the northern side of the island of Gozo 🇲🇹 malta

According to tradition, this is the cave referred to by Homer in The Odyssey. The nymph Calypso lived in this cave and it is where she entertained Ulysses for seven years before he resumed his journey. Calypso Cave is in fact a series of caves and, according to some these extend right down to the sea.

And many of the other authors in the anthology are great too.
